cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.RO, cs.AI, cs.SY

This paper deals with the problem of understanding driver behavior in complicated urban scenarios using multimodal signals including video, LiDAR and CAN bus data streams. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper proposes a novel approach called gated recurrent fusion units (GRFU) that learn fusion weighting and temporal weighting simultaneously, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also deals with autonomous navigation, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The paper proposes an end-to-end approach for learning both the vehicle/environment state and the driver policy, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the problem of tactical driver behavior classification, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
